The [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] historian [[Thucydides]] suggested in his late 5th century BC, ''[[History of the Peloponnesian War]]'', that tsunamis were related to [[submarine earthquake]]s,<ref name="Thucydides 3.89.1-4"/><ref name="Smid, T. C. 103f."/> but the understanding of a tsunami's nature remained slim until the 20th century and {{clarify span|much remains unknown|date=October 2012}}.  Major areas of current research include trying to determine why some large earthquakes do not generate tsunamis while other smaller ones do; trying to accurately forecast the passage of tsunamis across the oceans; and also to forecast how tsunami waves would interact with specific shorelines.

